[We thank Joerg Siedenburg for his thoughtful comments. The risk of
transmission is related to the infectiousness of the person with
tuberculosis, the duration of exposure, the proximity to the source
person, and the ventilation. Indeed, of the 6 investigations reported
by the U.S. CDC
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00036502.htm> following
exposure of others traveling on the same aircraft to persons with
infectious pulmonary TB (that is, a symptomatic patient with
acid-fast bacillus smear-positive cavitary pulmonary TB),
transmission of _M. tuberculosis_ is known to have occurred only on 2
occasions: once from a flight attendant to other flight crew, and
once from a passenger to other passengers seated in close proximity
on a flight of more than 8 hours duration. These exposures resulted,
fortunately, only in tuberculin skin test conversions, not active
tuberculosis at the time of the investigations; but because of this
disease's long latency, active tuberculosis may ultimately develop in
some of these tuberculin converters. If the exposed passengers had
the additional misfortune of being immunocompromised (for example by
HIV infection or immunosuppressive medication for auto-immune disease
or organ transplantation), the outcome could be much worse. - Mod.ML]
